              <table id="EditorialReviewsPanel" class="ReviewSection" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%"><tr><td>
	
                <DIV class="ReviewHeading">Book Description:</DIV>
                <span id="Label1">When John Muir traveled to California in 1868, he found the pristine mountain ranges that would inspire his life&#8217;s work. The Mountains of California is the culmination of the ten years Muir spent in the Sierra Nevadas, studying every crag, crook, and valley with great care and contemplation.<br><br>Bill McKibben writes in his Introduction that Muir "invents, by sheer force of his love, an entirely new vocabulary and grammar of the wild . . . a language of ecstasy and exuberance." <b><br><br>The Mountains of California</b> is as vibrant and vital today as when it was written over a century ago.  <br><br>This Modern Library Paperback Classic includes the photographs and line drawings from the original 1898 edition.<br></span>
              
</td></tr></table>
